.SH PORTSCAN
The
.B portscan
command provides direct scanner-engine control:
.TP
.B --type connect|syn|udp|ack|fin|null|xmas|window|maimon|ping|service
Choose the scan type.
.TP
.B \-T, --timing 0-5
Select the scanner timing template.
.TP
.B \-p, --ports SPEC
Use presets such as top100 or top1000, ranges such as 1-1024, or lists such as 22,80,443.
.TP
.B \-sV, --version
Enable service version detection.
.TP
.B \-O, --os
Enable OS fingerprinting.
.TP
.B --intensity 0-9
Set version detection intensity.
.TP
.B --raw-backend auto|nping|builtin
Choose the raw TCP backend for raw-style scan types.
.TP
.B --sudo, --elevate
Attempt a sudo or Administrator relaunch when a raw scan needs elevation.
.PP
Raw-style TCP modes such as syn, ack, fin, null, xmas, window, and maimon require
a raw-capable backend and elevated privileges. ASRFacet-Rb can use Nping across
Linux, macOS, and Windows when it is installed and the host has the required raw
packet support.
.SH CONSOLE
The console is the richest operator interface and supports framework-style commands such as:
.IP
show commands
.br
show options
.br
show workflow
.br
show config
.br
show learning
.br
info recon
.br
man
.br
wizard
.PP
Normal framework commands can also be run directly inside the console.
.SH WEB SESSION
Web session mode starts a local browser-facing control panel, bound to 127.0.0.1:4567
by default unless overridden.
It keeps saved sessions, live activity, report links, command previews, and built-in docs in one shell.
.PP
The web UI is local, not hosted. Drafts are stored under
.I ~/.asrfacet_rb/web_sessions/
and runs still use the same underlying reconnaissance and scanner surfaces as the CLI.
.SH LOCAL LAB
The local lab starts a safe placeholder validation target on 127.0.0.1:9292 by default.
It exposes intentionally weak headers, permissive CORS, JavaScript endpoint patterns,
debug-style routes, and reporting-friendly placeholder content so operators can test
the framework locally before using a real authorized target.
.SH DEPLOY
Deploy mode starts the web control panel and, by default, the local lab together.
It waits for readiness, prints the service URLs, and writes a runtime manifest under
.I ~/.asrfacet_rb/runtime/
unless overridden with
.B --manifest .
Use
.B --public
only when you intentionally want the stack bound to 0.0.0.0.
.SH RECON BASICS
Passive reconnaissance uses third-party data without touching the target.
Active reconnaissance confirms assets by making requests or opening connections.
Effective attack surface mapping combines both approaches, then ranks the results so
deeper testing focuses on the most valuable assets first.
